  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      ECGs are routinely performed in cardiology. Recently handheld ECGs have shown promise in
      screening for heart rhythm disorders. These are quick to perform and do not require the
      preparation that is needed for 12 lead ECGs. We wanted to test whether a novel handheld ECG
      recorder, Kardia 6L, which has the potential to record a 6 lead ECG is able to screen for ECG
      abnormalities, thereby obviating the need for a full 12 lead ECG. This may allow for earlier
      diagnosis and treatment.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
  <detailed_description>
    <textblock>
      The aim of analysis is to determine if the handheld 6 lead ECG can be used as a simple
      screener to identify patients who do not need a 12 lead ECG.
    </textblock>
  </detailed_description>
